SIMPLE: oblivion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Oblivion
<hw>Ob*liv"i*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>oblivio</ets>, akin to <ets>oblivisci</ets> to forget: cf. OF.
<ets>oblivion</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of forgetting, or
the state of being forgotten; cessation of remembrance;
forgetfulness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Second childishness and mere <qex>oblivion</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Among our crimes <qex>oblivion</qex> may be set.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The origin of our city will be buried in eternal
<qex>oblivion</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Official ignoring of offenses; amnesty, or general
pardon; <as>as, an act of <ex>oblivion</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>Sir J.
Davies.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Forgetfulness</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Oblivious</ent>⟦br⟧
